### Assistant [2026-07-05T09:12:27.283Z]
Two levels, and you'll want both:

**1. Unit tests → `moto`**
A Python library that patches `boto3` in-process to fake AWS services — no Docker, no network calls, tests run in milliseconds.
```python
import boto3
from moto import mock_aws

@mock_aws
def test_create_paste():
    ddb = boto3.resource("dynamodb", region_name="us-east-1")
    table = ddb.create_table(
        TableName="pastes",
        KeySchema=[{"AttributeName": "paste_id", "KeyType": "HASH"}],
        AttributeDefinitions=[{"AttributeName": "paste_id", "AttributeType": "S"}],
        BillingMode="PAY_PER_REQUEST",
    )
    table.put_item(Item={"paste_id": "abc1234", "content": "hello"})
    assert table.get_item(Key={"paste_id": "abc1234"})["Item"]["content"] == "hello"
```
This is what your pytest suite runs against for everyday business-logic tests — fast enough to run on every save.

**2. Integration / local dev → DynamoDB Local (official Docker image)**
`amazon/dynamodb-local` is Amazon's real Java-based implementation of the DynamoDB engine, just running on your machine instead of in AWS — same wire protocol, same conditional-write semantics, no AWS account or credentials needed.
```yaml
# docker-compose.yml
services:
  dynamodb-local:
    image: amazon/dynamodb-local
    ports: ["8000:8000"]
    command: "-jar DynamoDBLocal.jar -sharedDb -dbPath /data"
    volumes: ["./data/dynamodb:/data"]
```
Your FastAPI app points `boto3` at `endpoint_url="http://localhost:8000"` in dev/test config instead of the real AWS endpoint (same code path otherwise — just an env-var-driven endpoint override). This is what you run FastAPI against locally, and what CI spins up as a service container for integration tests that need real DynamoDB semantics (conditional puts for your collision check, etc.).

One caveat: DynamoDB Local doesn't actively enforce TTL expiry (it accepts the attribute but won't background-delete expired items) — irrelevant today since Pastes don't expire, but worth remembering if you add TTL later and need to test expiry behavior specifically (would require hitting real AWS for that one thing).

