### Assistant [2026-07-05T09:03:56.979Z]
ADR-001 created at `docs/architecture/adr/ADR-001-random-short-id.md`.

**Question 3: What's the ID format and length?**

This determines your DynamoDB partition key shape and collision-handling logic. Options:
- **Base62** (`0-9A-Za-z`), URL-safe with no special encoding needed.
- **Base58** (Bitcoin-style — drops `0`, `O`, `I`, `l`) to avoid visually-ambiguous characters when read aloud or hand-typed.

And length: 7 chars of base62 gives ~3.5 trillion combinations; 8 gives ~218 trillion. At any reasonable pastebin scale (millions to low billions of pastes), 7 chars keeps birthday-paradox collision odds effectively zero (need ~2M pastes before even a 1-in-a-million chance of one collision at 7 chars) while keeping URLs short.

My recommendation: **base62, 7 characters**, with a collision check on write (re-roll on conflict — at this ID space, you'll essentially never hit one, but the check is cheap insurance). Skip base58's ambiguity-avoidance — pastebin URLs are copy-pasted and clicked, not read aloud or transcribed by hand, so the extra restriction isn't buying you anything.

Agree, or do you want more headroom in the ID space?

