### User [2026-07-05T11:28:05.632Z]
can metadata like title and expiragtion exist in non auth enviroment ?

### Assistant [2026-07-05T11:28:19.696Z]
Yes — title, expiration, and syntax-highlighting are all per-paste attributes, not per-user ones. They don't need an account to exist: anonymous pastebin "Guest" users can set all three (we saw the expiration/title/syntax fields on the form while showing "Hello Guest, not logged in"). They'd just be new fields on the existing `Paste` item (`paste_id`, `content`, `created_at` → plus `title`, `expires_at`, `language`), enforced at write time — no ownership check needed.

What *does* need auth specifically is anything requiring "this paste belongs to a specific person": private visibility (only the owner can view), folders (per-user organization), and a "my pastes" archive listing. Password-protection and burn-after-read are also account-independent in principle (just extra attributes/logic on the paste itself), though burn-after-read conflicts with the current `Cache-Control: immutable` caching design and would need that reconciled.

So the auth line is really: **exposure/ownership features need auth, content/behavior attributes on a single paste don't.**

