### Assistant [2026-07-05T11:21:41.381Z]
I compared pastebin.com against the current app. Current templates (`create.html`, `view.html`, `404.html`) are completely unstyled — no CSS at all — while pastebin.com is a full commercial product: syntax highlighting, categories/tags, paste expiration, public/private/folder visibility, password protection, burn-after-read, titles, accounts/social login, comments/ratings/view counters, search, a public archive, raw/download/embed/print/report actions, ads, social share buttons, and browser/desktop/mobile apps.

Almost none of that fits copypaste's current scope: `Features.md` explicitly defers **auth/accounts** (which private pastes, folders, "my pastes" archive, and login all depend on) and **mutability**; there's no schema field for **title**, **expiration**, **category/tags**, or **syntax language**; and "burn after read" conflicts with the current immutable/cacheable design (`Cache-Control: immutable`). Ads, comments, ratings, social login, and native apps aren't part of this product's plan at all.

What genuinely fits with zero schema/scope changes: visual polish (dark theme, monospace font, styled textarea/button/layout) on the existing create/view/404 pages, plus the copy-to-clipboard interaction that's already sitting in `TASKS.md` phase 3 as deferred. A `raw/<id>` plaintext route is also a small, schema-free addition pastebin has.

