### User [2026-07-05T12:43:44.167Z]
why uv run cdk deploy and not just cdk deploy?

### Assistant [2026-07-05T12:44:07.291Z]
`cdk` itself is a separate Node.js CLI (globally installed via npm, not managed by `uv`) — it just orchestrates CloudFormation calls. But `cdk.json` tells it how to actually generate the templates: `"app": "python app.py"`. When you run `cdk deploy`, the CDK CLI shells out to run that command, and whatever `python` is first on `PATH` at that moment is what executes `app.py` — which needs `aws-cdk-lib` and `constructs` importable (installed only in `cdk/.venv` via `uv sync`).

If you just ran plain `cdk deploy` without `uv run`, `python app.py` would resolve to your system/default Python, which doesn't have those packages installed, and you'd get `ModuleNotFoundError: No module named 'aws_cdk'`. `uv run` puts `cdk/.venv` at the front of `PATH` for the whole command it wraps, so when `cdk` internally invokes `python app.py`, it picks up the right interpreter with the right dependencies.

